The Oathbound March names Shadowmere's founding operational doctrine: defense, levy, and dead-processing as one corridor duty.
Shadowmere was established as a fortified frontier march whose mandate combined three functions that other settlements kept separate.
Soldiers who guarded the march also collected transit levies; levy collectors also processed war dead and plague dead before they reached Midgaard's core districts.
The integration was deliberate: the Crown reasoned that a march combining these functions would be self-sustaining — levy revenue funded defense, defense protected the dead-processing operations, dead-processing maintained legal continuity for the march's population.
The March's oath structure bound soldiers, clerks, and processing staff to a single unified command; breaking the oath in one role voided the holding in all three.
This created both internal cohesion and internal pressure: a soldier who refused a processing duty could lose their levy-collection authority; a clerk who fled processing operations could lose their garrison protection.
The Oathbound March's institutional charter predates the Plague Mandate by at least two generations. The March was functioning when the emergency laws arrived.
The Plague Mandate's emergency powers were layered onto the existing March structure rather than replacing it, creating the compressed system that survived as Shadowmere's haunted administration.
The March's oaths were never formally dissolved. Midgaard issued annexation directives, rollback orders, and amnesty declarations — none were accepted by the March's command chain.
The Oathbound March's military dead, bound to emergency command articles that no surviving authority has rescinded, patrol Shadowmere's walls enforcing orders from a government that no longer exists.
The doctrine is operational. The government that issued it is not.

