Kowloon's Black Ledger includes the Oathbound March as a category-one institutional failure: a crisis-protocol system that achieved indefinite operational continuity beyond its designed scope.
The March's three-function integration is noted as technically impressive: the self-sustaining levy-defense-processing loop maintained function long after its external support collapsed.
Kowloon's crisis protocol designers reviewed the March's structure when developing the Neon Covenant's own integrated operations framework.
The March's integration model was partially adopted: Kowloon's crisis-period combined-function operations use the same logic of mutual support between revenue, defense, and administration.
The element Kowloon did not adopt was the unified oath structure: Kowloon's personnel hold function-specific oaths that expire with the crisis period, not unified oaths bound to institutional continuity.
The March's failure was oath design: a unified oath with no sunset condition creates an institution that cannot be peacefully dissolved when its mandate expires.
Kowloon's crisis operations include explicit sunset clauses in all integrated-function authorizations. This is called the March provision in internal governance documentation.
The Black Ledger's Oathbound March entry concludes: the March's military dead enforcing obsolete orders is not a horror story. It is a design failure with a documented cause.
Design the oath correctly and the institution dissolves correctly. Design it incorrectly and you get Shadowmere.

