Kiess's anti-secrecy doctrine treats the Oathbound March as the clearest case of emergency powers creating institutional permanence through opacity.
The March's oath structure was not publicly disclosed in its full scope when the March was chartered. The integration of levy, defense, and dead-processing under a single oath was buried in administrative annexes.
If the full oath structure had been publicly documented and subject to three-power review, a sunset condition would have been a minimum requirement.
No sunset condition was included. Kiess considers this a direct consequence of the opacity, not an oversight.
The Evermeet lesson applies again: when institutions hide their operational structure in administrative annexes, they create the conditions for that structure to outlast its mandate.
Kiess's frontier march doctrine — governing Kiess's own border operations along the Roc Road — includes full public disclosure of all oath structures and explicit sunset conditions.
This was not the norm when Kiess adopted it. It is now cited as a model by reform factions in both Midgaard and Rakuen.
Kowloon's march provision and Kiess's march doctrine were developed independently and reach similar conclusions through different institutional philosophies.
Kiess considers this convergence significant: transparency and crisis-protocol rigor both point toward the same design requirement. The March proves what happens when both requirements fail.

