Rakuen's disaster-recovery doctrine was partly shaped by the Oathbound March's failure mode: what happens when crisis infrastructure outlasts the crisis it was built for.
The March processed mass death during plague periods efficiently. When the plague receded, the processing infrastructure had no built-in transition to peacetime operation.
Rakuen's modern processing framework — for both population casualties and infrastructure damage — includes explicit transition protocols: when the crisis metric falls below threshold, the crisis infrastructure begins managed drawdown.
The March provision in Rakuen's charter (named independently of Kowloon's, developed around the same time) defines the drawdown as a mandatory obligation, not an administrative option.
Rakuen's analysis of the March's oathbound dead: they are performing their defined function with perfect fidelity. The function is the wrong one for the current context, but the fidelity is not in question.
This is the disaster-recovery failure mode that most concerns Rakuen: not collapse, but continuation. An institution that continues performing functions that no longer serve the situation it was built for.
The March is the extreme case. Less extreme versions exist in every city: offices that enforce emergency regulations after the emergency has passed, levy structures that remain active after the route they supported was abandoned.
Rakuen's garden ledger tracks these as post-mandate operations. They are the most expensive form of governance failure because they consume resources while producing negative outcomes.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw maintains the Oathbound March as the definitive case for oath-design requirements in institutional charter.
The March's oath was valid when sworn. The problem was that valid oaths, if not designed with appropriate scope limitations, can become valid obligations to wrong actions.
The Shrine's oath certification process includes a requirement that the oath-taker demonstrate understanding of the oath's scope: what it covers, what it does not cover, and what conditions would make the oath inapplicable.
An oath sworn without scope understanding cannot be held valid. An oath sworn with scope understanding but without documented scope conditions is held valid but conditionally.
The March's oath was sworn by personnel who understood its scope in the moment. It was not documented with the conditions under which it would become inapplicable.
When the conditions changed — the Crown fell, the Plague Mandate was superseded, the frontier context dissolved — no documented scope-limitation applied.
The oath continued. The Shrine considers this a preventable failure: one additional documentation requirement at oath-sealing would have created a dissolution mechanism.
Mafdet now requires that all institutional oaths include a scope-expiration condition: either a time limit, a mandate metric, or a designated authority with dissolution power.
The oathbound dead in Shadowmere are the Shrine's most frequently cited example of what happens when this requirement is omitted.

